The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 The state government on Friday approached Calcutta High Court seeking modification of the order on eviction of squatters along Rabindra Sarovar.

 dvocate-general Balai Ray told the division bench of Chief Justice V.S. Sirpurkar and Justice A.K. Ganguly: ?The state government has decided to provide 10 acres to rehabilitate the squatters. Mayor Bikash Ranjan Bhattacharya has been requested to chalk out a scheme to implement the decision. Following the changed circumstances, the government is seeking modification of the court order and time to settle the issue peacefully.? 

 ayor Bhattacharya, who appeared for the civic body, supported Ray?s submission.

 fter hearing the pleas, the bench asked the government to file an application on Monday, when the matter will come up for hearing again. 

 arlier, urban development minister Asok Bhattacharya had announced that the government had selected a 10-acre plot in Madurdaha, Sonarpur, where the settlers would be rehabilitated. 

 Six persons, including two women and a 10-year-old boy, were seriously injured at Friday noon, when a minibus on the Howrah-Beckbagan route overturned on Asutosh Chowdhury Avenue, off Ballygunge Post Office. 

 he injured were taken to Calcutta National Medical College, from where a few were shifted to two nursing homes. The bus was impounded but the driver managed to flee. Traffic in the area was disrupted for some time.

 Dense fog over Netaji Subhas Chandra International Airport delayed all morning flights on Friday. No flight could take off or land till 8.30 am. Normal services resumed later in the day. 

 Municipal commissioner Alapan Bandyopadhyay on Friday asked the conservancy department to evict pavement-dwellers in front of Chaplin Park, opposite the Central Municipal Building. The commissioner also asked for a report on how the dwellers had settled on the pavements.

 Raju Halder, a salesman of ITC, was assaulted and robbed of Rs 7,000 in Jagaddal, on the northern fringes of the city, on Friday. Police said Halder had collected the money from retailers and was on his way to deposit it with the company. 

 e was stopped by three youths, who demanded the money from him. As he refused, the three hit him with a blunt weapon. Halder was admitted to hospital.

 An 11-year-old-girl was allegedly raped in Kestopur on Thursday. The accused, Gopal Panda, has been arrested. Police said Panda had admitted to the crime. He has been remanded in judicial custody. The girl?s father works as a caretaker at a house in Salt Lake?s BL Block. 

 All files relating to civil engineering maintenance work of the Calcutta Municipal Corporation must contain photographs. The order was issued on Friday by municipal commissioner Alapan Bandyopadhyay. The commissioner directed the chief engineers that photographs should be taken before and after restoration work. 

 Veteran journalist Karunamoy Mullick, known as Shyamda, passed away at his Bagbazar house on Friday. He was 68 and is survived by his wife, one daughter and two sons.

